{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"0b536050-44e0-11ed-8501-ef4c51992106","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"28b4b27f-9062-4857-88d7-2ea5cd3d2e74","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Choosing a Forecast Target","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"c0f9a962-e83d-4f2f-a7df-848d89dd9ba6"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"b00f4ea6-c5b0-45f8-870d-1bcd742d78de","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Forecasting by assuming fixed ratios of sales is very common. Another approach is to forecast by targeting specific ratios that the company either wants or needs to maintain. For example, debt covenants (such as those discussed in ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"63847125-7028-4f61-a496-12f1cfe72575","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Chapter 15","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"52d11d40-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":") often require a company to maintain certain levels of liquidity or minimum interest coverage. The lender does this by specifying, for example, a minimum current ratio (current assets/current liabilities) of 1.5, or a minimum cash flow to interest ratio of 1.2. The company would then incorporate these target ratios into its forecasts to ensure it will be in compliance with its loan covenants.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"aafc37f9-1382-48d5-a5d5-c3b22beff0ce"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"c3326e40-3212-4686-b957-ab522a573286","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The need to consider other target ratios is an example of a larger issue in forecasting—that the firm’s investment, payout, and financing decisions are linked together and cannot be treated separately. As we saw in ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"ce2ec8a8-8dca-4430-979d-91f82ed6c0da","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Table 18.4","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"913b5af0-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":", the balance sheet must balance. So a financial manager must understand that the firm can set an investment budget and a financing plan, and those will then determine what is available to pay out. Alternatively, a firm could decide on an investment budget and payout policy, and those will then determine the firm’s financing position—perhaps in unintended ways. The bottom line is that a financial manager must balance all these linked decisions, and a careful forecast allows him or her to see the consequences of decisions.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"4706568c-3d7d-4d3b-b001-314fb6e560f0"}]}]}]},{"cssClass":"aside-group Sidebar_1Aside","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"f84af1c5-21fe-4f21-9e5f-f2cf79bb68ee","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Concept Check","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"b8ac2242-9e3d-4e33-9f0b-0bb3e49a7fdc"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"1","startValue":3},"ref":"50487443-ba0e-43b3-9e34-1e6faecde4ca","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"206c03c9-5120-4052-adf9-302fac2b7463","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"d3c56858-04bb-4f94-845a-13f937e28842","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"What is the basic idea behind the percent of sales method for forecasting?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"06eff787-73e0-4224-a21c-5e741bde1a24","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"57e34d47-eb7e-4b60-ab9c-98b271ece363","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"How does the pro forma balance sheet help the financial manager forecast net new financing?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"e39badde-33dd-48cb-96e7-d72529e3cfcd"}]}]}]}]},"screenType":"","transitions":{"enter":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""},"exit":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""}},"lockElements":false,"learnerCurrentAttempt":1,"footer":{"buttonText":"Next","buttonIcon":"Arrow","showFooter":false,"showHistoryNavButtons":false,"previewFooter":false,"position":"Fixed to screen bottom","footerComponent":{"showFooterDropArea":"hide","width":100,"footerComponentsAlignment":"right"}},"styles":{"background":{},"stage":{"maxWidth":940,"background":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","responsive":true,"padding":{"vertical":60,"horizontal":60},"border":{"color":"rgba(224, 224, 224, 1)","radius":0,"width":0}},"elements":{"padding":{"vertical":10,"horizontal":10}},"footer":{"buttonColor":"rgba(0, 115, 202, 1)","textColor":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)","backgroundColor":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","padding":10,"corners":4,"border":"none","shadow":"0 -1px 4px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.06), 0 0 12px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.1)"},"feedback":{"width":320,"textColor":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)","backgroundColor":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","corners":4,"border":"none","shadow":"0 5px 47px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.15), 0 10px 20px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.1), 0 7px 8px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.1)"}},"title":"Choosing a Forecast Target"},"assets":[],"scenarios":[],"pluginPayload":{"pluginRepositoryPath":"https://plugin-reposit